00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:10.850
BROMLEIGH MCCLENEGHAN:
Good afternoon.

00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:14.730
I'm very excited to
be with you today.

00:00:14.730 --> 00:00:18.040
When I learned that
Google did author talks

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:20.720
was a number of years ago, when
we had actually first written

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:21.770
our parenting book.

00:00:21.770 --> 00:00:24.110
But it was from a
fairly small press,

00:00:24.110 --> 00:00:30.030
and it was definitely written
for a limited churchy audience.

00:00:30.030 --> 00:00:32.090
And they didn't
think that it would

00:00:32.090 --> 00:00:33.390
be particularly interesting.

00:00:33.390 --> 00:00:36.610
But when I came to Lauren and
said, I have this book called,

00:00:36.610 --> 00:00:38.490
"Good Christian Sex,"
certainly people

00:00:38.490 --> 00:00:40.130
would be interested in that.

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:43.160
So I'm delighted to be here.

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:47.370
It's a funny topic to
be writing and talking

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:51.890
about as someone who
is working in churches.

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:56.072
This is not a particularly
academic text.

00:00:56.072 --> 00:00:58.030
One of the great things
about pastoral ministry

00:00:58.030 --> 00:00:59.790
is that I get to
be a generalist.

00:00:59.790 --> 00:01:01.960
So I get to write,
and I get to read,

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:04.340
and I get to hear
people's stories.

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:08.020
And I get to be a part of
the life of a community.

00:01:08.020 --> 00:01:13.010
And all of my education always
has been interdisciplinary,

00:01:13.010 --> 00:01:16.482
and so allows me to know about
a lot of different things.

00:01:16.482 --> 00:01:17.940
So we're going to
talk a little bit

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:21.740
today about some of the
biblical stories that

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:24.900
have shaped the way that
American Christians talk

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:26.660
about sexuality.

00:01:26.660 --> 00:01:30.970
But I am not someone who can
get into an argument with you

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:35.220
about the proper pronunciation
or meaning about the Greek

00:01:35.220 --> 00:01:36.290
or Hebrew.

00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:40.300
You are not going to
ever see my Greek grades

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:43.430
from that year in seminary.

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:48.490
Another thing that I don't
address in the book at any rate

00:01:48.490 --> 00:01:50.590
is some of the
biblical texts that

00:01:50.590 --> 00:01:53.140
are known in the church
as clobber passages.

00:01:53.140 --> 00:01:55.370
Those are the seven
that people like

00:01:55.370 --> 00:01:59.050
to trot out to bash queer
folks over the head with.

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:03.150
And I don't really
address those.

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:06.230
They've been looked at by
scholars on all kinds of sides

00:02:06.230 --> 00:02:07.120
of the issue.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:09.850
And so I don't really
talk about those.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.660
I don't want to parse what
has already been discussed.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:20.190
But I did think that there
was a place for this book.

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:25.410
So just to draw
nice, broad strokes.

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:28.760
In the Christian
tradition-- the part

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:31.050
of the Christian tradition
that I grew up in-- I'm

00:02:31.050 --> 00:02:32.829
a preacher's kid,
actually, who has now

00:02:32.829 --> 00:02:33.870
written a book about sex.

00:02:33.870 --> 00:02:35.410
My parents are
super proud of me.

00:02:35.410 --> 00:02:42.380
And the church that I grew up
in was progressive in some ways,

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.130
but also largely silent about
issues around sexuality--

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:48.090
about the experiences
of sexuality.

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:51.630
We had some, like,
Christian sex ed

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:55.990
that we were made to go to
as junior high students.

00:02:55.990 --> 00:03:00.190
Ours was led at least in part
by my father, which was not even

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:06.330
remotely awkward, and
didn't shape me at all.

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:08.830
But we learned a lot
about the creation story

00:03:08.830 --> 00:03:10.820
and God's good
gift of sexuality,

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:15.190
and then basically sort
of, use birth control.

00:03:15.190 --> 00:03:18.260
And that was sort of the
end of that discussion.

00:03:18.260 --> 00:03:21.710
And so for me personally, a
lot of the-- at least growing

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:25.050
up-- a lot of the narratives
that I had about what healthy

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:28.830
sexuality looked like came from
sophomore health class taught

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:34.290
by the JV basketball coach
and 90210 or "Dawson's Creek"

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:35.399
or, you know, you're 16.

00:03:35.399 --> 00:03:37.690
You should probably be sleeping
with whatever boyfriend

00:03:37.690 --> 00:03:39.540
you have.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:42.740
The other sort of strand of
American Christianity that

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:46.200
really started talking a
lot about sex in the '90s,

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:52.520
when I was a teenager,
continued an emphasis

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:56.880
that had begun in the
'80s when it first--

00:03:56.880 --> 00:04:00.400
when abstinence-only education
became a part of something that

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:02.452
could get funding in schools.

00:04:02.452 --> 00:04:04.660
It actually started during
the Reagan administration,

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:10.630
but sort of ramped up as
part of the Clinton welfare

00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:13.290
reform in '96.

00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:16.730
And then again, certainly,
when President Bush

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:20.960
introduced the Office of
Faith-based Initiatives.

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:22.460
And so they talked
a lot about that.

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:25.640
And that part of
Christianity really

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:31.030
emphasized abstinence only--
abstinence-only education

00:04:31.030 --> 00:04:34.570
and that teenagers,
young adults, everybody

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:38.450
should be fully chaste--
that was the word, chastity--

00:04:38.450 --> 00:04:39.730
until they were married.

00:04:39.730 --> 00:04:44.140
And anything outside of marriage
was problematic and wrong.

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:46.960
And that narrative
came to really dominate

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:51.010
what people understood was the
Christian understanding of what

00:04:51.010 --> 00:04:53.040
holy, good sex was.

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:56.260
And in our world,
and particularly

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:59.260
in the mainline
Protestant congregations

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:03.030
that we grew up in, that was--
I had no idea that was going on.

00:05:03.030 --> 00:05:08.530
By the time I read the sort of
seminal text of that movement,

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:11.490
"i Kissed Dating
Goodbye," by Josh Harris.

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:12.640
I was in grad school.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:15.080
And I read it, and I was like,
well, that ship has sailed.

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:17.350
I'm sort of done with that.

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:21.920
But I was also actually
really angry about it

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.200
because it's sort
of a terrible book.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:29.320
But also because the author,
who was at that point

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:36.360
just a 21-year-old kid
himself wrote this tome

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:42.220
that sort of suggested that--
not just sex, but really

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:46.720
any sort of feeling of
pleasure, or desire,

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:50.310
or of romantic relationship
outside of something that

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.650
was leading directly to
marriage-- and in fact

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:57.616
in the moment after
marriage-- was very wrong.

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:04.230
There's one book that he talks
about-- he has the first book,

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:05.688
"I Kissed Dating
Goodbye," and then

00:06:05.688 --> 00:06:07.910
he has the sequel is
when he met his wife

00:06:07.910 --> 00:06:12.650
and when they started courting--
they did courting, not dating,

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:13.500
which is holier.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:17.640
At one point, he's sitting
in a hammock-- they're

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:21.280
like head-to-foot, so they're
sitting next to each other

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:21.950
in a hammock.

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:26.110
And they're not even
really touching at all.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:31.100
But he looks, and he
starts to admire her legs.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:36.600
And he then is overcome by a
feeling of his own sinfulness.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:42.760
And he has to picture Jesus
bleeding on the cross in order

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:47.860
to right his mind and get his
mind out of the gutter again.

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:50.207
This is, like, a month
before their wedding.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:54.387
So that book had
a huge effect on--

00:06:54.387 --> 00:06:56.720
AUDIENCE: --you'd think it'd
mess up his wedding at all.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:06:57.280
BROMLEIGH MCCLENEGHAN: No.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:06:57.981
No.

00:06:57.981 --> 00:06:58.480
No.

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:00.780
They are going to just
totally set that baggage aside

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:03.420
right away.

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:07.970
But not only for them, but
for really a generation

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:10.020
of American
Christians growing up

00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:14.050
in a certain part of the
church, his book and others

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:16.270
then like it, along with
True Love Waits and some

00:07:16.270 --> 00:07:18.960
of these other movements,
really affected the way

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:21.060
that we talk about sexuality.

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:24.750
As someone who
identifies as a Christian

00:07:24.750 --> 00:07:29.990
and had some really wonderful
experiences before I

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:33.290
was married, I was
frustrated by the sense

00:07:33.290 --> 00:07:36.060
that somehow our sexuality
was something that

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:37.260
could be turned on and off.

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:38.770
There are a whole lot of
disciplines who tell you

00:07:38.770 --> 00:07:39.830
that's a terrible idea.

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:44.320
But also the fact
that healthy sexuality

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:47.090
was somehow wholly
distinct from what it

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:49.020
meant to be a faithful person.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:51.360
So this book has
sort of come out

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:55.770
of this cultural moment
and my personal experience,

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:58.820
but also a real
desire to just talk

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:00.830
about what it feels
like to fall in love,

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:02.413
and, like, meet
somebody that you want

00:08:02.413 --> 00:08:04.100
to touch and be touched by.

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:07.560
I'm ordained in the United
Methodist Church, which,

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:10.490
like many other
churches, we were often

00:08:10.490 --> 00:08:15.181
very silent on issues of what
healthy sexuality looked like.

00:08:15.181 --> 00:08:17.430
But we definitely have a,
like, don't ask, don't tell.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:18.914
You'll probably figure it out.

00:08:18.914 --> 00:08:20.330
If you really are
in a crisis, you

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:21.704
can come and talk
to your pastor,

00:08:21.704 --> 00:08:23.540
and maybe they will
give you good advise.

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:24.246
Maybe not.

00:08:24.246 --> 00:08:25.870
But the issue that
we really focused on

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:29.820
is LGBTQ inclusion around
ordination, around marriage.

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:33.260
That has been the dominant
conversation and fight.

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:35.830
And it's been ugly and horrible.

00:08:35.830 --> 00:08:39.029
And while some denominations
are on the better side of it,

00:08:39.029 --> 00:08:41.070
the Methodist Church is
still really mired in it.

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:48.350
And so part of my hope then,
too, in addressing these topics

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:52.887
is to help offer an entry point.

00:08:52.887 --> 00:08:54.470
I don't think all
people are the same,

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:56.261
and all people believe
all the same things.

00:08:56.261 --> 00:09:00.850
But I do think that it
can be helpful to folks

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:06.030
to give them a way to
identify with other people.

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:08.650
So I kind of wanted to
unpack the experience

00:09:08.650 --> 00:09:11.740
of falling in love, or
of seeking pleasure,

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:13.918
or of following your desires.

00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:20.430
So the book takes up
questions of sexuality,

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:23.700
but also relationships and love.

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:25.740
And then the final
impetus-- I now

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:27.960
work in a local congregation.

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:30.490
But I used to work at the
University of Chicago.

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:34.960
And so I worked with a lot of
college students and graduate

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:35.950
students.

00:09:35.950 --> 00:09:41.030
And certainly with some
of the Title IX stuff,

00:09:41.030 --> 00:09:42.790
and just being on
a college campus,

00:09:42.790 --> 00:09:48.379
you can't ignore the very
open wounds of rape culture.

00:09:48.379 --> 00:09:49.420
That's really all around.

00:09:49.420 --> 00:09:52.060
The questions about what's
the nature of consent?

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:53.170
And how do we get it?

00:09:53.170 --> 00:09:55.670
And how do we ask for it?

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:58.940
There's lots of hand-wringing
about hook up culture.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:03.590
And I really wanted to
not do hand-wringing.

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:04.200
I don't know.

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:07.600
I went to college,
and I met some people.

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:09.080
But at the same
time, I was talking

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:10.830
to a friend of mine
just the other day who

00:10:10.830 --> 00:10:13.910
is a college chaplain.

00:10:13.910 --> 00:10:17.950
And she and her husband, who's
on the faculty at the college

00:10:17.950 --> 00:10:20.920
where she works also--
the students came to them,

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:27.290
and they wanted the couple
to do panel discussion

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:29.590
on how you date.

00:10:29.590 --> 00:10:32.780
They know how to get wasted
and sleep with somebody

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:33.800
they don't really know.

00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:38.610
But they have no idea
how to build intimacy.

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:42.400
Aside from any
moral questions we

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:45.880
might have about what it means
that you have to knock yourself

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:48.270
out in order to
pursue something,

00:10:48.270 --> 00:10:52.140
it's very hard to
have enjoyable,

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:55.030
pleasurable experiences
if you can't communicate

00:10:55.030 --> 00:10:56.570
at all with your partner.

00:10:56.570 --> 00:11:00.620
So there's probably some need to
like teach communication skills

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:02.280
to people.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:05.220
So that's my interest
in-- for younger readers.

00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:10.090
So that's kind of the framework
in which this book came out of.

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:13.360
And so I wanted to
then share with you--

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:14.900
since the introduction
to the book

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:18.310
went up on a Facebook
first reads program,

00:11:18.310 --> 00:11:20.240
I've started getting
all kinds of comments.

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:22.073
I know I've really made
it because I finally

00:11:22.073 --> 00:11:23.600
started getting trolled.

00:11:23.600 --> 00:11:27.356
All these folks
who are convinced

00:11:27.356 --> 00:11:28.730
that I am a heretic
and a sinner,

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:30.438
and I am leading people
down the primrose

00:11:30.438 --> 00:11:31.770
path all the way into hell.

00:11:31.770 --> 00:11:34.400
And they like to
pull out Bible verses

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:38.640
to tell me why I am wrong
for suggesting that sexuality

00:11:38.640 --> 00:11:40.530
is a part of who we are.

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:44.470
And that our bodies are
not separate from our minds

00:11:44.470 --> 00:11:47.010
or spirits, but that
we're all sort of just

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:49.750
humans with bodies, and
souls, and all these things.

00:11:49.750 --> 00:11:53.920
And that focusing on sexual
ethics, which is my interest,

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:56.890
as opposed to sexual
morality, is a problem.

00:11:56.890 --> 00:11:58.930
So they proof text
about all the things.

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:00.680
You have to shun fornication.

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:03.485
And don't you know your body
is a temple of the Holy Spirit.

00:12:03.485 --> 00:12:04.360
And all these things.

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:15.770
And so I try to engage the Bible
in-- it's certainly not new,

00:12:15.770 --> 00:12:16.890
but a different way.

00:12:16.890 --> 00:12:18.770
I don't want to proof text.

00:12:18.770 --> 00:12:23.040
The great Christian
ethicist-- she just retired,

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:26.060
I believe, from Yale-- I mean,
I believe she just retired.

00:12:26.060 --> 00:12:26.970
She was at Yale.

00:12:26.970 --> 00:12:32.390
Margaret Farley wrote
this wonderful book

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:34.170
called, "Just Love."

00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:38.250
And it's sort of a
Christian sexual ethics.

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:43.300
And I mean, it's firmly
within the tradition

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:44.670
of Christian ethics.

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:50.700
But she challenges
enough-- she's not a nun,

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:52.170
but she's taken orders.

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:56.337
So she's a Catholic holy woman.

00:12:56.337 --> 00:12:58.420
I can't think of what the
word I'm looking for is.

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:00.300
But she's a woman religious.

00:13:00.300 --> 00:13:03.000
There you go.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.830
And she got in trouble with
the Vatican for this book.

00:13:05.830 --> 00:13:06.740
So it's great.

00:13:06.740 --> 00:13:09.890
You know it's good when it's
been knocked by the Vatican.

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:12.300
But it's very much in
keeping with the tradition.

00:13:12.300 --> 00:13:14.750
But she has this
great line that's

00:13:14.750 --> 00:13:17.060
basically like, you
shouldn't proof text

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:18.130
the Bible about anything.

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:21.270
But you really shouldn't proof
text the Bible about sexuality.

00:13:21.270 --> 00:13:23.980
Proof texting, of course,
means just pulling things out

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:26.690
of context and then sort of
saying, well, here it is.

00:13:26.690 --> 00:13:30.980
Here's the coherent
list of rules

00:13:30.980 --> 00:13:33.620
that we've got right here.

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:36.530
Because that's really just
not how the Bible is written.

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:39.240
It was written over an
extended period of time

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:40.910
by multiple authors.

00:13:40.910 --> 00:13:44.140
Parts of it are-- and
have always been--

00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:46.070
understood as allegorical.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:48.930
Parts of them are histories
intentionally offered

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:51.936
from different perspectives.

00:13:51.936 --> 00:13:53.310
Parts of them are
letters written

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:59.150
to very particular communities
at different moments in time.

00:13:59.150 --> 00:14:01.240
