is, institutions are doing
what they're supposed to do.

00:42:09.810 --> 00:42:11.460
They're inherently conservative.

00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:15.170
They're supposed to keep
things the same over time.

00:42:15.170 --> 00:42:20.620
And so helping
institutions which

00:42:20.620 --> 00:42:25.290
are inherently conservative
to adapt to social changes

00:42:25.290 --> 00:42:28.340
is ongoing work and doesn't
happen very quickly.

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:34.200
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
that the current view

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:37.020
is relatively recent.

00:42:37.020 --> 00:42:39.460
There's a whole different
spread of ages here.

00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:42.370
So my entire life, as far
as I've been able to tell,

00:42:42.370 --> 00:42:46.580
the dominant Christian viewpoint
has been abstinence only.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:47.140
This is bad.

00:42:47.140 --> 00:42:49.050
And so on.

00:42:49.050 --> 00:42:55.831
So how do you think that
can-- to say be changed sounds

00:42:55.831 --> 00:42:58.080
like going in and like forcing
other people to believe

00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:00.720
something else, which
isn't good either.

00:43:00.720 --> 00:43:02.560
But besides, I
guess, writing a book

00:43:02.560 --> 00:43:03.685
that might perhaps appeal--

00:43:03.685 --> 00:43:05.810
BROMLEIGH MCCLENEGHAN:
That's what I'm going to do.

00:43:05.810 --> 00:43:07.539
What are you going to do?

00:43:07.539 --> 00:43:10.080
AUDIENCE: How would you suggest
going about-- as you've seen,

00:43:10.080 --> 00:43:12.500
on your Facebook page, you
mentioned lots of people

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:15.480
take offense to
what you're saying.

00:43:15.480 --> 00:43:17.690
How do you think we
can help spread it

00:43:17.690 --> 00:43:22.947
into the country and
even beyond the country?

00:43:22.947 --> 00:43:25.030
BROMLEIGH MCCLENEGHAN: In
the church, for example,

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:29.040
in trying to shift the way that
we talk about sexuality, we,

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:34.140
for the last generation,
in the mainline church,

00:43:34.140 --> 00:43:36.190
we've talked about
rights language.

00:43:36.190 --> 00:43:38.250
And we've talked about justice.

00:43:38.250 --> 00:43:42.200
And I think that's
critically important.

00:43:42.200 --> 00:43:44.960
I mean, you don't do ethics
without a concern for justice,

00:43:44.960 --> 00:43:45.700
right?

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:47.210
That's not very good ethics.

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:55.770
But I think that you
change hearts and minds

00:43:55.770 --> 00:43:59.540
by building bridges, and
inviting conversation,

00:43:59.540 --> 00:44:02.660
and asking people to reflect
on their experiences.

00:44:02.660 --> 00:44:07.010
In the first church
that I served,

00:44:07.010 --> 00:44:10.260
it was a super tiny congregation
with basically little

00:44:10.260 --> 00:44:11.050
old ladies.

00:44:11.050 --> 00:44:17.060
And our town was
increasingly home

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:21.700
to this-- the town had--
the chamber of commerce

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:25.400
had specifically started
encouraging members

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:28.490
of the queer community to
move to it because they had

00:44:28.490 --> 00:44:31.390
great affordable bungalows,
and it was close to the city,

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:32.690
and it was great.

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:37.509
And so for this reason, like,
we have this growing population.

00:44:37.509 --> 00:44:39.550
We should have this
conversation about sexuality.

00:44:42.276 --> 00:44:44.402
And to see if we could
make a public statement

00:44:44.402 --> 00:44:46.360
about whether or not they
would be welcome here

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:47.264
in this congregation.

00:44:47.264 --> 00:44:49.180
And so we started having
this conversation, me

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:55.970
and all the old ladies,
and in some ways,

00:44:55.970 --> 00:44:57.840
it was just such a
surprising thing.

00:44:57.840 --> 00:45:00.910
We started having a
conversation, and this one

00:45:00.910 --> 00:45:05.070
woman, Liz, who may or
may not yet be living,

00:45:05.070 --> 00:45:07.180
but she said, you know,
when I got married,

00:45:07.180 --> 00:45:08.700
I married a Catholic.

00:45:08.700 --> 00:45:11.780
And the priest wouldn't
marry us because it was

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:14.140
just outside of the practice.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:17.240
And she was like,
it's the same thing.

00:45:17.240 --> 00:45:19.980
In her mind, her experience
of being turned away

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:24.230
from the church because
of who she was-- it

00:45:24.230 --> 00:45:25.730
was totally analogous.

00:45:25.730 --> 00:45:31.710
And so I think by asking-- I
mean, it's a little different.

00:45:31.710 --> 00:45:35.300
But I think encouraging
people to think

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:38.320
about their experiences
and how they

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:40.620
might be similar to other
people's experiences

00:45:40.620 --> 00:45:43.310
I think can be a
way of doing that.

00:45:43.310 --> 00:45:45.750
And then for the
church, I think we

00:45:45.750 --> 00:45:48.610
have to do the nitty gritty
work of looking at the text

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:51.200
and reflecting on our
theology and making

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:56.530
the case that there's an
alternative-- that there's not

00:45:56.530 --> 00:46:01.229
only one Christian way
of talking about this.

00:46:01.229 --> 00:46:02.020
AUDIENCE: Thank you

00:46:02.020 --> 00:46:03.000
BROMLEIGH MCCLENEGHAN: Thanks.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:03.500
OK.

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:04.850
Thank you.

